# 3. Definitions

### Parallel System

A system with multiple processors working simultaneously.

---

### Shared Memory

All CPUs share the same RAM and disk.

---

### Shared Nothing

Each node has its own CPU, memory, and disk.

---

### Shared Disk

Each node has its own memory, but disk is shared.

---

### NUMA (Non-Uniform Memory Access)

Memory is shared but **access time varies depending on location**.

---

### Horizontal Partitioning

Splitting table rows across multiple machines.

---

### Distributed Lock Manager

System that coordinates locks across multiple machines.

---

### Cache Coherency

Ensures all nodes see consistent data in memory.

---

### Thread Migration

Moving threads between processes to balance load.

---

# 4. Detailed Explanation

---

# 4.1 Shared Memory Architecture

## What it is

* All CPUs access same memory + disk
* uniform access time

## How it works

* OS schedules workers across CPUs
* shared structures (buffer pool, locks) accessible to all

## Why it matters

* simplest model
* widely used

## When used

* modern servers (multi-core, SMP systems)

---

## Key Challenge

> Parallelizing a single query across CPUs

---

## Advantages

* simple programming
* no data partitioning
* fast communication

---

## Limitations

* contention on shared memory
* limited scalability

---

# 4.2 Shared-Nothing Architecture

## What it is

* cluster of independent machines
* no shared memory or disk

---

## How it works

### Step-by-step

```text
1. Data is partitioned across nodes
2. Query arrives at one node
3. Query is distributed
4. Each node processes local data
5. Results are combined
```

---

## Data Partitioning

* hash-based
* range-based
* round-robin
* hybrid

---

## Why it matters

* enables massive scalability

---

## Advantages

* near-linear scalability
* minimal contention
* cost-efficient

---

## Challenges

### 1. Partitioning quality

Bad partitioning → skew → poor performance

---

### 2. Coordination

Required for:

* transactions
* deadlock detection
* two-phase commit

---

### 3. Failure Handling

Options:

1. shutdown all nodes
2. data skip (partial results)
3. redundancy (best approach)

---

### Chained Declustering

* spreads copies across nodes
* failure load distributed evenly

---

## When used

* data warehouses
* large-scale analytics

---

# 4.3 Shared-Disk Architecture

## What it is

* nodes have separate memory
* disk is shared

---

## How it works

* each node runs DBMS
* accesses same disk

---

## Advantages

### 1. No partitioning needed

Simplifies administration

---

### 2. Better fault tolerance

Node failure ≠ data loss

---

## Problems

### 1. Data consistency

Same data in multiple RAM copies

---

### 2. Coordination required

Solutions:

* distributed lock manager
* cache coherence protocol

---

### 3. Bottlenecks

* coordination overhead
* contention

---

### 4. Storage failure risk

Corruption affects all nodes

---

## When used

* enterprise systems

Examples:

* Oracle Real Application Clusters
* IBM Db2 for zSeries SYSPLEX

---

# 4.4 NUMA Architecture

## What it is

* shared memory system
* but access time differs

---

## How it works

* memory divided into regions (pods)
* each CPU has local memory

---

## Why it matters

* improves scalability over shared memory

---

## Challenges

* remote memory access slower
* performance degradation

---

## Optimization Strategies

1. Use local memory
2. keep workers on same CPU

---

## Key Insight

> Memory locality becomes critical

---

## When used

* modern large shared-memory systems

---

# 4.5 DBMS Threads & Multi-processors

## Problem

DBMS threads inside one process:

```text
Only 1 CPU used
```

---

## Solution

Use multiple OS processes:

```text
Process1 → CPU1
Process2 → CPU2
```

---

## New Challenge

Load imbalance:

```text
Some processes busy, others idle
```

---

## Solution: Thread Migration

Move threads across processes dynamically

---

## Design Decisions

* number of processes
* thread allocation
* load distribution

---

## Rule of Thumb

```text
1 process per CPU
```

---

## Key Insight

> Concurrency ≠ parallelism

---

